  "response_text": "The average initial risk attitude of social learning agents remains constant throughout the 100-year simulation period across all repeated runs, with values distributed between approximately -0.11 and 0.18. This temporal invariance persists from the initial time step through the final time step, with each simulation run maintaining its specific constant value without deviation.\n\nThe range of values, spanning from negative dispositions around -0.11 to positive values around 0.18, indicates that the repeated simulations explore diverse baseline risk attitudes. In the context of the grazing system, these constant values represent the fixed initial disposition of farmers to deviate from recommended livestock numbers, established at the outset of each simulation. The lack of temporal adaptation reflects that this metric captures a static parameter rather than a learning or evolving risk perception, enabling analysis of how different starting risk profiles influence long-term pasture management outcomes and household persistence under stationary behavioral assumptions."  
}

